Have you ever deployed a Docker container on AWS Lambda?If yes briefly explain?

Yes! Docker Container on AWS Lambda

Yes, I have deployed Docker containers on AWS Lambda. Instead of uploading a ZIP file, I built a Docker image using the AWS Lambda base image, pushed it to ECR, and created a Lambda function pointing to that ECR image. This approach is useful when your dependencies exceed Lambda's 250 MB ZIP limit or when you need a custom runtime. The handler function remains the same — Lambda just runs it inside the container instead of a ZIP package.

What It Means

Normal Lambda:
  upload ZIP file
  max 250 MB ❌
  limited dependencies

Container Lambda:
  upload Docker image to ECR
  max 10 GB ✅
  any dependencies
  any runtime ✅
----

How It Works

Write Dockerfile
        ↓
Build Docker image
        ↓
Push to ECR
        ↓
Create Lambda function
  → select Container image
  → point to ECR image
        ↓
Lambda runs your container ✅

-----

Lambda Console
→ Create function
→ Container image  ← select this
→ Browse ECR images
→ Select your image ✅
→ Create function ✅
---

Container Lambda vs ZIP Lambda

ZIP Lambda:
  ✅ simple
  ✅ fast deploy
  ❌ max 250 MB
  ❌ limited runtimes

Container Lambda:
  ✅ max 10 GB
  ✅ any runtime
  ✅ any dependencies
  ✅ reuse existing Docker
  ⚠️ slower cold start
  ⚠️ needs ECR

Limits

Container Lambda limits:
  Image size    : max 10 GB ✅
  Memory        : 128 MB - 10 GB
  Timeout       : 15 minutes max
  Concurrency   : 1000 default

