Explain horizontal vs vertical scaling in real infra scenarios?

"In our production setup we use both. For web and application tier we use horizontal scaling — ASG automatically adds EC2 instances and HPA adds Kubernetes pods based on CPU metrics, with ALB distributing traffic. This gives us zero downtime and handles traffic spikes efficiently. For our database tier we start with vertical scaling — upgrading RDS instance class — because it's simpler and maintains data consistency. When reads become a bottleneck we add RDS Read Replicas for horizontal read scaling."

"Blue-Green is the ideal approach for zero downtime vertical scaling and AWS RDS supports it natively. However in practice teams skip it for smaller systems because it doubles the database cost during switchover.


 vertical scaling options for instance:

Option 1: Maintenance window
  Upgrade at 3 AM ✅
  Accept downtime ✅
  Simple and cheap ✅

Option 2: Blue-Green deployment
  Zero downtime ✅
  Costs double temporarily ❌
  Best for 24/7 apps ✅

Option 3: Multi-AZ failover
  Upgrade standby first
  Failover to standby
  ~60 seconds downtime ✅
  Better than cold upgrade ✅

